The accessibility rule violated here is related to the lack of an `alt` attribute on the `<img>` element. According to the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.2, all non-text content should have a text alternative that serves the equivalent purpose. This is covered under guideline 1.1.1 Non-text Content (Level A).

The `alt` attribute is important because it provides a textual description of the image for users who cannot see it. This includes people who use screen readers due to visual impairments, as well as users who have images turned off or are experiencing a slow internet connection where images might not load.

Here's why the given HTML snippet violates WCAG 2.2:

1. The `<img>` element lacks an `alt` attribute, which means that assistive technologies like screen readers cannot convey the content or function of the image to users who rely on them.
2. Without an `alt` attribute, the image is not accessible to people who cannot see it, and they may miss out on important information or functionality represented by the image.

To correct this violation, you should add an `alt` attribute to the `<img>` element with a brief description of the image's content or function. If the image is purely decorative and does not convey any important information, you can use an empty `alt` attribute (`alt=""`) to indicate this to assistive technologies.

Here is a corrected version of the HTML that is fully accessible:

```html
<img class="rewardsIcon" 
     style="height: 20px !important;
            width: 20px !important;
            position: absolute;
            left: -25px;
            top: -1px;
            max-width: 20px;
            max-height: 20px;" 
     src="https://www.arabinstruments.com/static/frontend/Codazon/unlimited_sport/en_US/Mirasvit_Rewards/images/icon.png"
     alt="Rewards icon">
```

In this corrected version, I've added `alt="Rewards icon"` to provide a meaningful description for the image. If the image is meant to be decorative, you would use `alt=""` instead:

```html
<img class="rewardsIcon" 
     style="height: 20px !important;
            width: 20px !important;
            position: absolute;
            left: -25px;
            top: -1px;
            max-width: 20px;
            max-height: 20px;" 
     src="https://www.arabinstruments.com/static/frontend/Codazon/unlimited_sport/en_US/Mirasvit_Rewards/images/icon.png"
     alt="">
```

By including an appropriate `alt` attribute, you ensure that the image is accessible to all users, regardless of their ability to see it.

The accessibility rule violation `aria-valid-attr-value` refers to the use of ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) attributes in a way that does not conform to the values expected for those attributes. In the provided HTML snippet, the `aria-describedby` attribute is used. This attribute is intended to provide an accessible description for an element, where the value of the attribute should be the ID of another element that contains the description.

In the snippet, `aria-describedby="gallery-1-43285"` is used, but without the corresponding element with the ID `gallery-1-43285` present in the HTML, the value does not point to a valid ID. This means that assistive technologies like screen readers will not be able to find the description that is supposed to be associated with the image, which violates the WCAG 2.2 guidelines for providing descriptive text for non-text content.

To correct this, you would need to ensure that there is an element with the ID `gallery-1-43285` that contains a description of the image. Here's how you might correct the HTML:

```html
<img width="120" height="120" src="https://www.avpgalaxy.net/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Screenshot_20211112-114018_Gallery-120x120.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail" alt="Description of the image content" decoding="async" loading="lazy" aria-describedby="image-description">

<div id="image-description" class="visually-hidden">
  Detailed description of the image for screen reader users.
</div>
```

In this corrected version, I've done the following:

1. Provided an `alt` attribute with a brief description of the image. This is important for users who cannot see the image, as the `alt` text serves as a textual alternative.
2. Added a `div` element with an ID that matches the value of the `aria-describedby` attribute. This `div` contains a more detailed description of the image, which can be read by screen readers.
3. Added a `class="visually-hidden"` to the `div` element. This is a common technique used to hide content visually but keep it accessible to screen readers. You would need to define the `.visually-hidden` class in your CSS with styles that remove the element from the visual flow without hiding it from assistive technologies.

Here's an example of what the CSS for `.visually-hidden` might look like:

```css
.visually-hidden {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  margin: -1px;
  padding: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  border: 0;
}
```

By making these changes, the image now complies with WCAG 2.2 guidelines by providing both a short alternative text and a longer description for users who rely on assistive technologies.
